{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:23:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:23:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17352"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17352"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.11,0.71,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10042"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70617"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10042"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56082"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"10025"},{"type":"tags","id":"10029"},{"type":"tags","id":"11220"},{"type":"tags","id":"11221"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23712"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70617"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDrug metabolism is essential for converting lipophilic compounds into more water-soluble forms that can be excreted from the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes Phase I drug metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conjugation with glucuronic acid","Addition of acetyl groups","Oxidation, reduction and hydrolysis reactions","Methylation reactions","Addition of sulphate groups"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidation, reduction and hydrolysis reactions\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary mechanisms of Phase I drug metabolism. These reactions are mainly catalysed by the cytochrome P450 enzyme system in liver hepatocytes. Phase I reactions introduce or expose functional groups on drug molecules, making them more polar.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent Phase II conjugation reactions:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjugation with glucuronic acid\u003C/strong\u003E - This is glucuronidation, a Phase II reaction\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of sulphate groups\u003C/strong\u003E - Sulphation is a Phase II conjugation reaction\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethylation reactions\u003C/strong\u003E - Methylation is a Phase II conjugation process\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of acetyl groups\u003C/strong\u003E - Acetylation is a Phase II conjugation mechanism\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EPhase I reactions typically precede Phase II conjugation reactions, though some drugs may undergo Phase II metabolism directly. The overall purpose is to increase water solubility for excretion via the kidneys or bile.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phase I drug metabolism primarily involves oxidation, reduction, and hydrolysis reactions catalysed by cytochrome P450 enzymes.","Phase II drug metabolism involves conjugation reactions that increase water solubility for excretion.","Most drug metabolism occurs in the liver hepatocytes, though some occurs in other tissues."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56082"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17352"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56082"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T09:46:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T09:53:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10042"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70617"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17